# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mesh-connectivity-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] In computer science, **binary space partitioning** (**BSP**) is a method for space partitioning which recursively subdivides a Euclidean space into two convex sets by using hyperplanes as partitions.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] This process of subdividing gives rise to a representation of objects within the space in the form of a tree data structure known as a **BSP tree**.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Binary space partitioning was developed in the context of 3D computer graphics in 1969.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The structure of a BSP tree is useful in rendering because it can efficiently give spatial information about the objects in a scene, such as objects being ordered from front-to-back with respect to a viewer at a given location.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Other applications of BSP include: performing geometrical operations with shapes (constructive solid geometry) in CAD, collision detection in robotics and 3D video games, ray tracing, virtual landscape simulation, and other applications that involve the handling of complex spatial scenes.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Binary space partitioning is a generic process of recursively dividing a scene into two using hyperplanes until the partitioning satisfies one or more requirements.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] It can be seen as a generalization of other spatial tree structures such as *k*-d trees and quadtrees, one where hyperplanes that partition the space may have any orientation, rather than being aligned with the coordinate axes as they are in *k*-d trees or quadtrees.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] When used in computer graphics to render scenes composed of planar polygons, the partitioning planes are frequently chosen to coincide with the planes defined by polygons in the scene.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The specific choice of partitioning plane and criterion for terminating the partitioning process varies depending on the purpose of the BSP tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] For example, in computer graphics rendering, the scene is divided until each node of the BSP tree contains only polygons that can be rendered in arbitrary order.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] When back-face culling is used, each node, therefore, contains a convex set of polygons, whereas when rendering double-sided polygons, each node of the BSP tree contains only polygons in a single plane.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] In collision detection or ray tracing, a scene may be divided up into primitives on which collision or ray intersection tests are straightforward.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Binary space partitioning arose from computer graphics needing to rapidly draw three-dimensional scenes composed of polygons.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] A simple way to draw such scenes is the painter's algorithm, which produces polygons in order of distance from the viewer, back to front, painting over the background and previous polygons with each closer object.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] This approach has two disadvantages: the time required to sort polygons in back-to-front order, and the possibility of errors in overlapping polygons.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] A disadvantage of binary space partitioning is that generating a BSP tree can be time-consuming.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Typically, it is therefore performed once on static geometry, as a pre-calculation step, prior to rendering or other real-time operations on a scene.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The expense of constructing a BSP tree makes it difficult and inefficient to directly implement moving objects into a tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The canonical use of a BSP tree is for rendering polygons (that are double-sided, that is, without back-face culling) with the painter's algorithm.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Each polygon is designated with a front side and a backside which could be chosen arbitrarily and only affects the structure of the tree but not the required result.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Such a tree is constructed from an unsorted list of all the polygons in a scene.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Make a node *N* in the BSP tree, and add *P* to the list of polygons at that node.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] If that polygon is wholly behind the plane containing *P*, move that polygon to the list of nodes behind *P*.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] If that polygon is intersected by the plane containing *P*, split it into two polygons and move them to the respective lists of polygons behind and in front of *P*.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] If that polygon lies in the plane containing *P*, add it to the list of polygons at node *N*.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Apply this algorithm to the list of polygons in front of *P*.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Apply this algorithm to the list of polygons behind *P*.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The following diagram illustrates the use of this algorithm in converting a list of lines or polygons into a BSP tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] At each of the eight steps (i.-viii.), the algorithm above is applied to a list of lines, and one new node is added to the tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The final number of polygons or lines in a tree is often larger (sometimes much larger) than the original list, since lines or polygons that cross the partitioning plane must be split into two.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] It is desirable to minimize this increase, but also to maintain reasonable balance in the final tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The choice of which polygon or line is used as a partitioning plane (in step 1 of the algorithm) is therefore important in creating an efficient BSP tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] A BSP tree is traversed in a linear time, in an order determined by the particular function of the tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Again using the example of rendering double-sided polygons using the painter's algorithm, to draw a polygon *P* correctly requires that all polygons behind the plane *P* lies in must be drawn first, then polygon *P*, then finally the polygons in front of *P*.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] If this drawing order is satisfied for all polygons in a scene, then the entire scene renders in the correct order.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] This procedure can be implemented by recursively traversing a BSP tree using the following algorithm.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Otherwise, the viewing location *V* must be exactly on the plane associated with the current node.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] The tree is traversed in linear time and renders the polygons in a far-to-near ordering (*D1*, *B1*, *C1*, *A*, *D2*, *B2*, *C2*, *D3*) suitable for the painter's algorithm.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] BSP trees are often used by 3D video games, particularly first-person shooters and those with indoor environments.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] Game engines using BSP trees include the Doom, Quake, GoldSrc and Source engines.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] In them, BSP trees containing the static geometry of a scene are often used together with a Z-buffer, to correctly merge movable objects such as doors and characters onto the background scene.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] While binary space partitioning provides a convenient way to store and retrieve spatial information about polygons in a scene, it does not solve the problem of visible surface determination.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/binary-space-partitioning] BSP trees have also been applied to image compression.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A **bounding volume hierarchy** (**BVH**) is a tree structure on a set of geometric objects.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] All geometric objects, which form the leaf nodes of the tree, are wrapped in bounding volumes.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These nodes are then grouped as small sets and enclosed within larger bounding volumes.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These, in turn, are also grouped and enclosed within other larger bounding volumes in a recursive fashion, eventually resulting in a tree structure with a single bounding volume at the top of the tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Bounding volume hierarchies are used to support several operations on sets of geometric objects efficiently, such as in collision detection and ray tracing.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Although wrapping objects in bounding volumes and performing collision tests on them before testing the object geometry itself simplifies the tests and can result in significant performance improvements, the same number of pairwise tests between bounding volumes are still being performed.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] By arranging the bounding volumes into a bounding volume hierarchy, the time complexity (the number of tests performed) can be reduced to logarithmic in the number of objects.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] With such a hierarchy in place, during collision testing, child volumes do not have to be examined if their parent volumes are not intersected (for example, if the bounding volumes of two bumper cars do not intersect, the bounding volumes of the bumpers themselves need not be checked for collision).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The choice of bounding volume is determined by a trade-off between two objectives.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the one hand, bounding volumes with a very simple shape can be stored in only a few bytes, and intersection tests and distance computations are simple and fast.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the other hand, bounding volumes should fit the corresponding data objects very tightly.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One of the most commonly used bounding volumes is an axis-aligned minimum bounding box.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The axis-aligned minimum bounding box for a given set of data objects is easy to compute, requires only a few bytes to store, and robust intersection tests are easy to implement and extremely fast.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In terms of the structure of BVH, it has to be decided what degree (the number of children) and height to use in the tree representing the BVH.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A tree of a low degree will be of greater height.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] That increases root-to-leaf traversal time.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] On the other hand, less work has to be expended at each visited node to check its children for overlap.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The opposite holds for a high-degree tree: although the tree will be of smaller height, more work is spent at each node.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In practice, binary trees (degree = 2) are by far the most common.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One of the main reasons is that binary trees are easier to build.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] There are three primary categories of tree construction methods: top-down, bottom-up, and insertion methods.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The most crucial part for this approach is to decide how to partition objects in a node's region among the node's children.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This can be done with a splitting plane to split a node's bounding volume into partitions so that having to traverse many child nodes is minimized.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Simply using the midpoint of volume centroids for splitting might be a sub-optimal choice, as illustrated in the figure, where a big overlap volume occurs.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hence, good splitting criteria such as the surface-area heuristic (SAH) are often used with equal-size buckets of splitting planes, so that only at these splitting points, re-calculation of SAH is required.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] One example for this is the use of a Z-order curve (also known as Morton-order), where clusters can be found by simply taking a linear pass through a Morton-ordered array of leaves.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Given the independent clusters of leaf nodes, sub-trees can be constructed in parallel and then further combined to form higher nodes.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This parallelization makes the BVH construction very fast and can also be implemented in a hybrid manner, where all sub-trees are combined followed by a top-down approach.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Both top-down and bottom-up methods are considered *off-line methods* as they both require all objects to be available before construction starts.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] *Insertion methods* build the tree by inserting one object at a time, starting from an empty tree.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The insertion location should be chosen that causes the tree to grow as little as possible according to a cost metric.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Insertion methods are considered *on-line methods* since they do not require all objects to be available before construction starts and thus allow updates to be performed at runtime.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] After a BVH tree is constructed, it can then be converted to a compacted form for efficient traversal to improve overall system performance.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The compact representation is often a linear array in memory, where the nodes of the BVH tree are stored in depth-first order.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hence, for a binary BVH tree, the first child of an internal node will be placed next to itself, and only the offset from the interior node to the index of the second child must be stored explicitly.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The implementation of the traversal can be done without recursive function calls and only a stack is required to store the nodes to be visited next.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The pseudocode provided below is a simple reference for ray tracing applications.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs are often used in ray tracing to eliminate potential intersection candidates within a scene by omitting geometric objects located in bounding volumes which are not intersected by the current ray.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This only requires a small change in line 11-12 of the above pseudo-code.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Similar optimizations during BVH traversal can be employed when descending into child volumes of the second volume, to restrict further search space and thus reduce traversal time.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs also naturally support inserting and removing objects without full rebuild, but with resulting BVH having usually worse query performance compared to full rebuild.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs can also be combined with scene graph methods, and geometry instancing, to reduce memory usage, improve structure update and full rebuild performance, as well as guide better object or primitive splitting.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVHs are often used for accelerating collision detection computation.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In the context of cloth simulation, BVHs are used to compute collision between a cloth and itself as well as with other objects.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Another powerful use case for BVH is pair-wise distance computation.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A naive approach to find the minimum distance between two set of objects would compute the distance between all of the pair-wise combinations.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] A BVH allows us to efficiently prune many of the comparisons without needing to compute potentially elaborate distance between the all objects.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] BVH can significantly accelerate ray tracing applications by reducing the number of ray-surface intersection calculations.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hardware implementation of BVH operations such as traversal can further accelerate ray-tracing.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Currently, real-time ray tracing is available on multiple platforms.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Hardware implementation of BVH is one of the key innovations making it possible.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In 2018, Nvidia introduced RT Cores with their Turing GPU architecture as part of the RTX platform.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] RT Cores are specialized hardware units designed to accelerate BVH traversal and ray-triangle intersection tests.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The combination of these key features enables real-time ray tracing that can be use for video games. as well as design applications.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] AMD's RDNA (Radeon DNA) architecture, introduced in 2019, has incorporated hardware-accelerated ray tracing since its second iteration, RDNA 2.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] The architecture uses dedicated hardware units called Ray Accelerators to perform ray-box and ray-triangle intersection tests, which are crucial for traversing Bounding Volume Hierarchies (BVH).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] In RDNA 2 and 3, the shader is responsible for traversing the BVH, while the Ray Accelerators handle intersection tests for box and triangle nodes.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Originally designed to accelerate ray tracing, researchers are now exploring ways to leverage fast BVH traversal to speed up other applications.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] These include determining the containing tetrahedron for a point, enhancing granular matter simulations, and performing nearest neighbor calculations.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] Some methods repurpose Nvidia's RT core components by reframing these tasks as ray-tracing problems.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/bounding-volume-hierarchy] This direction seems promising as substantial speedups in performance are reported across the various applications.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] The **doubly connected edge list** (**DCEL**), also known as **half-edge data structure**, is a data structure to represent an embedding of a planar graph in the plane, and polytopes in 3D.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] This data structure provides efficient manipulation of the topological information associated with the objects in question (vertices, edges, faces).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] It is used in many algorithms of computational geometry to handle polygonal subdivisions of the plane, commonly called planar straight-line graphs (PSLG).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] For example, a Voronoi diagram is commonly represented by a DCEL inside a bounding box.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] This data structure was originally suggested by Muller and Preparata for representations of 3D convex polyhedra.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Simplified versions of the data structure, as described here, only consider connected graphs, but the DCEL structure may be extended to handle disconnected graphs as well by introducing dummy edges between disconnected components.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] DCEL is more than just a doubly linked list of edges.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] In the general case, a DCEL contains a record for each edge, vertex and face of the subdivision.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each record may contain additional information, for example, a face may contain the name of the area.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each edge usually bounds two faces and it is, therefore, convenient to regard each edge as two "half-edges" (which are represented by the two edges with opposite directions, between two vertices, in the picture on the right).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each half-edge is "associated" with a single face and thus has a pointer to that face.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] *All* half-edges associated with a face are clockwise or counter-clockwise.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] For example, in the picture on the right, all half-edges associated with the middle face (i.e. the "internal" half-edges) are counter-clockwise.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] A half-edge has a pointer to the next half-edge and previous half-edge of the same face.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] To reach the other face, we can go to the twin of the half-edge and then traverse the other face.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each half-edge also has a pointer to its origin vertex (the destination vertex can be obtained by querying the origin of its twin, or of the next half-edge).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each vertex contains the coordinates of the vertex and also stores a pointer to an arbitrary edge that has the vertex as its origin.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] Each face stores a pointer to some half-edge of its outer boundary (if the face is unbounded then pointer is null).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] It also has a list of half-edges, one for each hole that may be incident within the face.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/doubly-connected-edge-list] If the vertices or faces do not hold any interesting information, there is no need to store them, thus saving space and reducing the data structure's complexity.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] A **quad-edge** data structure is a computer representation of the topology of a two-dimensional or three-dimensional map, that is, a graph drawn on a (closed) surface.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] It was first described by Jorge Stolfi and Leonidas J.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] It is a variant of the earlier winged edge data structure.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] The fundamental idea behind the quad-edge structure is the recognition that a single edge, in a closed polygonal mesh topology, sits between exactly two faces and exactly two vertices.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] The quad-edge data structure represents an edge, along with the edges it is connected to around the adjacent vertices and faces to encode the topology of the graph.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Each quad-edge contains four references to adjacent quad-edges.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Each of the four references points to the next edge counter-clockwise around either a vertex or a face.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Each of these references represent either the origin vertex of the edge, the right face, the destination vertex, or the left face.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Each quad-edge reference points to a quad-edge and the rotation (from 0 to 3) of the 'arm' it points at.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] The quad-edge structure gets its name from the general mechanism by which they are stored.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] A single Edge structure conceptually stores references to up to two faces, two vertices, and 4 edges.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] The four edges stored are the edges starting with the two vertices that are attached to the two stored faces.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Much like winged edge, quad-edge structures are used in programs to store the topology of a 2D or 3D polygonal mesh.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] The mesh itself does not need to be closed in order to form a valid quad-edge structure.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Using a quad-edge structure, iterating through the topology is quite easy.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Often, the interface to quad-edge topologies is through directed edges.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] This allows the two vertices to have explicit names (start and end), and this gives faces explicit names as well (left and right, relative to a person standing on start and looking in the direction of end).
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] The four edges are also given names, based on the vertices and faces: start-left, start-right, end-left, and end-right.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] A directed edge can be reversed to generate the edge in the opposite direction.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/quad-edge] Iterating around a particular face only requires having a single directed edge to which that face is on the left (by convention) and then walking through all of the start-left edges until the original edge is reached.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] In computer graphics, the **winged edge** data structure is a way to represent polygon meshes in computer memory.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] It is a type of boundary representation and describes both the geometry and topology of a model.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] Three types of records are used: vertex records, edge records, and face records.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] Given a reference to an edge record, one can answer several types of adjacency queries (queries about neighboring edges, vertices and faces) in constant time.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] This kind of adjacency information is useful for algorithms such as subdivision surface.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] The **winged edge** data structure explicitly describes the geometry and topology of faces, edges, and vertices when three or more surfaces come together and meet at a common edge.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] The ordering is such that the surfaces are ordered counter-clockwise with respect to the innate orientation of the intersection edge.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] Moreover the representation allows numerically unstable situations like that depicted below.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] The winged edge data structure allows for quick traversal between faces, edges, and vertices due to the explicitly linked structure of the network.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] It serves adjacency queries in constant time with little storage overhead.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] This rich form of specifying an unstructured grid is in contrast to simpler specifications of polygon meshes such as a node and element list, or the implied connectivity of a regular grid.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] An alternative to the winged edge data structure is the Half-edge data structure.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] The face and vertex records are relatively simple, while the edge record is more complex.
[src:mesh-connectivity-structure/winged-edge] In short, the edge record has references to all its adjacent records, both when traversing around an adjacent vertex or around an adjacent face.
